  37,137,You ňĻMeccansňļ certainly pass by their ruins day
  37,138,and night. Will you not then understand
  37,139,And Jonah was indeed one of the messengers
  37,140,ňĻRememberňļ when he fled to the overloaded ship
  37,141,"Then ňĻto save it from sinking,ňļ he drew straws ňĻwith other passengersňļ. He lost ňĻand was thrown overboardňļ"
  37,142,Then the whale engulfed him while he was blameworthy
  37,143,Had he not ňĻconstantlyňļ glorified ňĻAllahňļ
  37,144,he would have certainly remained in its belly until the Day of Resurrection
  37,145,"But We cast him onto the open ňĻshoreňļ, ňĻtotallyňļ worn out"
  37,146,and caused a squash plant to grow over him
  37,147,We ňĻlaterňļ sent him ňĻbackňļ to ňĻhis city ofňļ at least one hundred thousand people
  37,148,"who then believed ňĻin himňļ, so We allowed them enjoyment for a while"
  37,149,"Ask them ňĻO Prophetňļ if your Lord has daughters,¬†while the pagans ňĻprefer toňļ have sons"
  37,150,Or ňĻask themňļ if We created the angels as females right before their eyes
  37,151,"Indeed, it is one of their ňĻoutrageousňļ fabrications to say"
